Using graphs, decide whether each inverse is a function. Figures are side by side (uniform size) with
concise captions. Below each pair, the reasoning lines up the “ ⇒ ” arrows and the verdict is boxed.
Construct inverse : reflect graph of y = p ( x ) across y = x ⇒ graph of p − 1
Apply VLT to p − 1  : some verticals cut the graph twice ⇒ Inverse is not a function
Domain/Range swap : Dom( p − 1 ) = Ran( p ) , Ran( p − 1 ) = Dom( p )
i Inverse of a line (reflection across y = x ).
Construct inverse : reflect non-vertical line across y = x ⇒ another non-vertical line
Apply VLT to f − 1  : each vertical meets at most once ⇒ Inverse is a function
Domain/Range swap : Dom( f − 1 ) = Ran( f ) , Ran( f − 1 ) = Dom( f )
